Compared to the C12-CDs before sulfonation, the content of element O in C12-SCDs increases significantly, mainly from the oxygen in the sulfonate groups. It could be seen from the C 1s high-resolution spectrum in Fig. 3(c) that element C is composed of four structures: π-π* (289.34 eV), CO (288.38 eV), C–N (285.98 eV), CC/C–C (284.80 eV), and C–S (283.08 eV). Compared to C12-CDs, the content of CC decreases slightly, indicating that the part of CC is oxidized in the process of sulfonation [24]. Significantly, the occurrence of C–S corresponds to the elemental analysis results in Table 1. The three peaks of the high-resolution spectrum of S 2p (Fig. 3(d)) at 168.54 eV, 169.67 eV, and 171.51 eV are referred to as -C-S(O
                           x
                        )-C (x = 2, 3, and 4) sulfone bridges, respectively. It can be seen from the infrared spectrum of Fig. S1(b) that the broad absorption peak of C12-CDs and C12-SCDs at 3125 cm−1 is the bending vibration absorption peak of O–H, and the apparent absorption peak at 2922 and 2849 cm−1 come from the bending vibration and stretching vibration of C–H in the long chain of dodecylamine. In addition, the CO and CC stretching vibration absorption peaks appear at 1629 cm−1 and 1547 cm−1, respectively. These absorption peaks indicate that the sulfonated C12-SCDs have a similar structure to C12-CDs. The existence of SO stretching vibration at 1061 cm−1 and 1011 cm−1 and C–S stretching vibration peak at 581 cm−1 proves the existence of the sulfonate groups, which is consistent with the results of the XPS analysis.
